# Data Drift Detection Standards

This document defines standards for detecting and responding to data drift in ML systems.

---

## Types of Drift

| Drift Type | Description | Detection Method |
|------------|-------------|-----------------|
| Feature drift | Input distribution changes | KS test, PSI, histogram comparison |
| Concept drift | Relationship between features and target changes | Performance monitoring |
| Label drift | Target distribution changes | Chi-squared test, distribution comparison |
| Upstream drift | Data source schema or quality changes | Schema validation, completeness checks |

---

## Detection Methods

### Population Stability Index (PSI)

| PSI Value | Interpretation | Action |
|-----------|---------------|--------|
| < 0.10 | No significant drift | Continue monitoring |
| 0.10 - 0.25 | Moderate drift | Investigate, consider retraining |
| > 0.25 | Significant drift | Retrain model, investigate root cause |

```python
import numpy as np

def compute_psi(reference: np.ndarray, current: np.ndarray, bins: int = 10) -> float:
    """Compute Population Stability Index."""
    ref_hist, bin_edges = np.histogram(reference, bins=bins)
    cur_hist, _ = np.histogram(current, bins=bin_edges)

    ref_pct = ref_hist / ref_hist.sum() + 1e-6
    cur_pct = cur_hist / cur_hist.sum() + 1e-6

    psi = np.sum((cur_pct - ref_pct) * np.log(cur_pct / ref_pct))
    return float(psi)
```

### Kolmogorov-Smirnov Test

```python
from scipy import stats

def detect_drift_ks(reference: np.ndarray, current: np.ndarray, alpha: float = 0.05) -> bool:
    """Detect drift using two-sample KS test."""
    statistic, p_value = stats.ks_2samp(reference, current)
    return p_value < alpha
```

